properties.Title: Update: Flood Warning Being Issued For The Lakes Within Whiteshell Provincial Park
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a Flood Warning for the Whiteshell Lakes due to increased precipitation in the area. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as levels and flows are rising. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing water or waters of unknown depth. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-10-18T14:45:00-05:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization, 2019-10-17T14:52:20-05:00, DD261AE0-E70D-853F-8C87-FF5FB19B15F0
Area: Whiteshell Provincial Park

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant prolonged rainfall is expected. Total rainfall: 60 to 100 mm. Locations: From Natuashish to Hopedale. Timespan: Beginning near noon Friday and tapering off to showers Sunday afternoon. Remarks: Rainfall amounts could exceed warning criteria of 75 mm in 48 hours. It is also likely that some snow will accumulate over the highest elevations of the inland terrain. Anyone using mountain trails should be prepared for winter weather. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2019-10-18T16:30:14-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-18T00:31:14-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.0781188653.2019
Area: Hopedale and vicinity, Nain and vicinity
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A prolonged period of significant coastal rain and high-elevation snow is expected. Total rainfall: 30 to 50 mm near Nain and 60 to 90 mm near Natuashish. Total snowfall: 10 to 20 cm inland and over higher terrain. Timespan: this morning until Sunday afternoon. Remarks: Rain, at times heavy, is expected along the north coast of Labrador today through Sunday. Over the higher elevations inland, precipitation will fall as heavy accumulating snow until midday Saturday before changing to a mixture of rain and wet snow. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Be prepared for possible winter conditions at higher elevations. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2019-10-19T00:10:39-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-18T08:11:39-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2612178002.2019
Area: Nain and vicinity

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A short period of significant rainfall is expected. Total rainfall: localized areas of 20 to 30 mm in heavy downpours. Locations: eastern and southern Avalon Peninsula. Timespan: early this morning until midday today. Remarks: Rain will spread northward across the Avalon Peninsula early this morning with a risk of thundershowers over southern parts of the peninsula. Rainfall rates of 5 to 10 mm per hour are possible in the heaviest downpours. The precipitation is expected to taper to occasional showers or drizzle around noon. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2019-10-18T20:59:24-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-18T08:36:24-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2424473589.2019
Area: Avalon Peninsula North, Avalon Peninsula Southeast, St. John's and vicinity, Avalon Peninsula Southwest
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A low pressure system tracking northeastwards out of the northern Prairie provinces will spread snow into Whale Cove, Rankin Inlet, and Chesterfield Inlet on Friday. The snow may be mixed at times with rain, which may limit accumulations initially, before precipitation intensifies Friday night into Saturday. Total accumulations will likely be in the 10 to 15 cm range by the time the snow tapers off on Sunday. This snowfall warning may be expanded to Naujaat later today for heavy snowfall expected on Saturday into Sunday. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-19T00:12:44-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-18T08:13:44-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.1324037704.2019
Area: Rankin Region including Whale Cove, Chesterfield Inlet

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A disturbance tracking northeastward out of the Northwest Territories spread snow into Baker Lake this afternoon which will continue tonight. The snow should taper off to light on Friday morning. Total accumulations of 10 to 15 cm are expected along with southeast winds gusting to 70 km/h and blowing snow at times. Another disturbance will spread more snow into the area Friday afternoon but this should become mixed with rain Friday evening which will limit snowfall amounts with the next system. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-18T12:29:55-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-17T20:30:55-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2378820420.2019
Area: Baker Lake
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. An area of high pressure situated over the Arctic Ocean and an intense low pressure system over the Gulf of Alaska will continue to produce conditions favourable for strong, gusty winds near the Richardson Mountains. The strong winds, falling snow and existing snow pack will combine to produce blizzard conditions today and tonight. The winds will gradually ease on Saturday. ### Travel is expected to be extremely hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 4 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-19T04:02:13-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-18T12:03:13-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.0683490124.2019
Area: Dempster
